    {
      "id": "intro-0",
      "sectionId": "intro",
      "title": "Intro",
      "body": "Ardunio programming cheat-sheet for I/O programming and  ardunio board programming."
    },
    {
      "id": "s1-1",
      "sectionId": "s1",
      "title": "Gather Necessary Materials",
      "body": "• Arduino Board: Any model, such as Arduino Uno, Mega, Nano, etc.\n• USB Cable: Compatible with your Arduino board (commonly USB Type-A to Type-B for Uno).\n• Computer: Windows, macOS, or Linux."
    },
    {
      "id": "s1-2",
      "sectionId": "s1",
      "title": "Install the Arduino IDE",
      "body": "• windows/mac/linux\n• Go to the Arduino Software page.\n• Download the os installer.\n• Run the installer and follow the instructions."
    },
    {
      "id": "s1-3",
      "sectionId": "s1",
      "title": "Connect Your Arduino Board",
      "body": "• Connect the Arduino board to your computer using the USB cable.\n• The power LED on the Arduino should light up, indicating it’s receiving power."
    },
    {
      "id": "s1-4",
      "sectionId": "s1",
      "title": "Configure the Arduino IDE",
      "body": "• Open the Arduino IDE.\n• Select Your Board:\n• Go to Tools > Board and select the model of your Arduino board (e.g., Arduino Uno).\n\n• Select the Port:\n\n• Go to Tools > Port and select the port that the Arduino is connected to (it usually shows as COMx on Windows,\n\n/dev/cu.usbmodemxxxx on macOS, and /dev/ttyUSBx on Linux)."
    },
    {
